thThe labels at pin endpoints aren't registering as connected — KiCad requires the label to be on a wire, or the pin endpoint to coincide with the label AND be recognized. Apparently placing a label at a pin endpoint alone isn't enough; ERC wants a wire or the label attachment point exactly on the pin. Interesting — the net names ARE shown (net GND, net VBUS_PROT), meaning the label position matched the pin (KiCad assigned the net name from the label!) but still reports "not connected to any wire or label."

Wait, it says "Symbol J3 pin 4 (net GND): not connected to any wire or label". So KiCad DID associate the net GND with the pin (from the label), but still flags unconnected. This is the classic "pin not connected to any wire" — a label on a pin with no wire is considered dangling. Actually the presence of the net name suggests the label is at the pin, but KiCad still wants a wire segment.

The fix: add a short wire from each pin endpoint, and put the label on the wire. Simplest: add a tiny wire stub at each pin endpoint (e.g., from pin endpoint extending a bit), and the label at the same endpoint will then attach to the wire.

Actually the real rule: a pin is "connected" if a wire endpoint touches it. A label alone does not connect a pin. The net name is derived because the label happens to be at that coordinate, but the pin still needs a wire.

So I need to add wire stubs at every labeled pin. That's ~24 wires. Let me add a short wire at each pin endpoint. A wire from the pin endpoint to a nearby point; the label should sit on the wire (at the pin endpoint, which is one end of the wire).

